Crate root for `steno`, the compiler from `.steno` theory source into Plover JSON dictionaries and LSP snippet artifacts. This file itself contains no logic — it declares the module tree and re-exports the public API each submodule owns — but it is the map an editor needs to find where a given piece of behavior actually lives, since almost everything downstream imports through these re-exports rather than reaching into submodules directly.

The pipeline is strictly one-way and staged: `parse` (fenced source text to an entry AST) → `expand` (fan-out counts, type-append chains, one-liner variants) → `render` (Plover dicts in plain/smart profiles, LSP snippets, `@literal` structural blocks). Every error type (`ExpandError`, `RenderError`, `SnippetError`, `StenoError`, `StrokeError`) carries a 1-based source line where applicable — any new fallible pass should follow that convention to stay consistent with existing error reporting. Data only flows forward through these stages; nothing in the library writes files — that's reserved for the `build-dict`, `build-nvim`, `measure`, and `viz-data` binaries, so adding file I/O here would break that separation.

Module responsibilities, per re-export list: `stroke` handles raw steno key/stroke encoding (`KeySet`, `StrokeKeys`, `parse_stroke`/`render_stroke`, count bit manipulation via `CountBank`/`CountBit`/`apply_count`); `parse` builds the `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr` AST from source text; `expand` turns parsed entries into `ExpandedEntry`/`TypedEntry` via type sets (`TypeDef`, `TypeOptions`, `TypeSet`, `build_type_set`) and count/flag expansion; `render` produces final dictionaries (`build_plain_dict`, `build_smart_dict`, `render_plain`, `render_smart`, wrapped in `BuildResult`); `snippet` builds LSP snippets with explicit sentinel markers (`SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE`) marking placeholder regions; `editor` models cursor/keystroke behavior for smart-editor profiles (`EditorState`, `Behaviors`, `Event`, `interpret`, `movement_events`, with `PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT` as named behavior presets); `blocks` emits `@literal` structural text (`emit_struct`, `struct_text`); `json_out` is a custom JSON serializer (`OrderedMap`, `to_json`, `json_string`) — used instead of `serde_json` presumably to control key ordering in output dictionaries, which matters if diffing generated JSON against fixtures.

Any change to a re-exported name here is a breaking change for all four binary crates (`build-dict`, `build-nvim`, `measure`, `viz-data`), which are the only consumers of this library.